title: For Sale/Trade:  1898 Krag-Jorgenson
postcontent: I rarely shoot this baby, so it's going up for sale.  Up for sale is a beautiful 1898 Krag-Jorgenson rifle. The receiver is marked for the 1899 Springfield, so I'm assuming it was converted to a rifle during a refurbishment or is possibly an experimental trial variant. The stock is intact with no cracks. The bore is pristine; clean with no pitting and good rifling. The metal finish has turned to patina, while the wood looks to be in good shape with the original finish. The rear sight is a 1902 variant. Serial number dates the rifle to September of 1900. This is a great example of the nicest US military rifle with a bolt as smooth as glass. The sling on the rifle is an M1 green web sling. Also comes with a brass muzzle/front sight cover and the stock oil bottle.  The rifle will also come with a Lee reloading die set, and 80 pieces of brass.  I am looking to get $800 for the whole package. Or $700 simply for the rifle.  Or trade for a Ross Rifle, genuine Mosin sniper rifle, PTR/C-308 rifle, Arsenal AK.  PM if interested. I'm located in NE Philadelphia, but spend most of my time up in Bucks.

Two 10 round magazines or one 20/30 round magazine will fit.- The stock and trigger mechanism can be folded forward for added safety and to facilitate secure storage or carry under extreme conditions. The SU-16 has a conventional, long-stroke gas-piston operation and utilizes the proven Johnson/Stoner breech locking system. It is compatible with standard AR-15/M-16 magazines. The reciprocating bolt handle and magazine catch are on the right side, while the push bolt safety can be changed to work from either side. Except for barrel and operating components, the SU-16 is made entirely of high impact reinforced polymer.Calibers: .223 Rem / 5.56mmWeight unloaded: 5.0lbs. / 2.3kgLength Open: 37.4" / 950.0mmLength Closed: 26.4" / 670.6mmBarrel length: 18.5" / 470.1mm *Magazine Capacity: 10 roundsBarrel Diameter: 3/4" to 5/8" / 19.1mm to 15.9mmTwist: 1:9" 1:228.6mmBolt Travel: 4.1" / 104mmTrigger Pull: 5lbs to 7lbs / 22.2N to 31.1NBarrel Weight: 26.1oz / 738.8g

While he was impressed with the quality and how well it matched (he was here in the office examining it), he passed because of the refinishing.        With that information, I'm going to lower the price! Going to repost the original information as well:       A 1917 DWM Artillery Luger! As you can see in the pictures, I tore this beauty down all the way to the firing pin and the numbers match internally and externally. The ONLY number that doesn't match is the magazine. What's cool though is, the magazine has the older style wooden knob on it.   This Luger does have wear, as you can see, but the patina on those areas adds to the beauty of this hard to find and amazing piece of history. It cycles just as smooth as you can imagine as well.       If you've been looking for an artillery Luger, you won't find one at a price this low.
